rawContent:
A gypsy in Paris pick pocketed me many moons ago. He stood next to me explaining how the public phones worked. I felt his hand gently lift my wallet from my jacket's pocket. He continued talking to me as if nothing happened, oblivious that I knew what was going on.

I stepped back ever so slightly and out of the corner of my eyes saw him holding my wallet behind his back. Realising that he would run away with my wallet if I reacted suddenly, my only option was to pick pocket him!

So I gently placed my hand on the wallet and slowly prised it out of his hands. He was astonished and gave me an instant compliment before he walked away empty handed.

I wonder if he told his fellow gang of pick pocketers that he was pick pocketed? 

The moral of the story is to consider one's options before reacting. A lesson from Victor Frankel's Man's Search for Meaning, "Between stimulus and response there is a space that is our power to choose our response. In our response lies our growth and freedom."
